    <p><h2>📍 Korkai:The Pearl Metropolis of the Pandyan Kingdom</h2>
<h4>Overview</h4>Korkai was an ancient port city and one of the earliest capitals of the Pandya kingdom. It is located near the Tamirabarani river and was once a thriving center of trade and commerce.As a premier maritime hub of the ancient world, Korkai was globally renowned as the "Pearl City," the epicenter of a lucrative pearl fishery that dominated the Gulf of Mannar. Its strategic position at the mouth of the Tamiraparani River allowed it to flourish as an international emporium, where Pandyan kings exported high-quality pearls, conch shells, and spices to the Roman Empire, Greece, and Egypt. This wealth and global prestige are immortalized in Sangam literature and the accounts of classical geographers like Ptolemy, who recorded the port as "Kolkhoi".
<br><br><center><img src="pic8.jpg" height="200" width="350"></center>
<h4>Key Discoveries</h4>Excavations have uncovered pottery, beads, shells, and tools related to pearl fishing. These findings indicate that Korkai was deeply involved in maritime activities and trade.The excavations at Korkai provide tangible evidence of its status as a maritime powerhouse, most notably through the discovery of specialized chank-cutting centers and heaps of discarded pearl oysters. The presence of black-and-red ware pottery inscribed with Tamil-Brahmi characters confirms a literate merchant class, while imported Roman Rouletted ware validates its extensive Mediterranean trade routes. Additionally, the recovery of diverse beads made of semi-precious stones and glass, alongside sophisticated fishing gear, highlights a community that had mastered both the extraction of sea resources and the high-value gem industry of the ancient world.
<h4>Historical Importance</h4>Korkai played a crucial role in international trade, connecting Tamil Nadu with other parts of the ancient world. It was especially famous for its pearl industry, which attracted traders from distant regions.Korkai served as the primary economic engine of the Pandyan Kingdom, acting as a global emporium that bridged South India with the Roman Empire, Egypt, and China. Its fame was built on the Gulf of Mannar's pearl fisheries, which were considered the most productive in the ancient world and provided the "principal income" for the royal treasury. This international prestige is solidified in Sangam literature, where works like Madurai Kanchi and Silappathigaram describe the city's immense wealth and its kings as the "Lords of Korkai". By facilitating a robust exchange of luxury goods for foreign gold and wine, Korkai helped establish the early urban and cultural foundations of Tamilakam. 
<h4>Cultural Insight</h4>The site reflects a society that was economically strong and globally connected through trade and commerce.The prosperity of Korkai illustrates a society that was not merely self-sufficient, but an economic heavyweight of the ancient era. Its ability to maintain global connectivity across thousands of miles of ocean proves a highly organized infrastructure of navigation and financial systems. This legacy of commerce shows that the early Pandyas were masterful strategists, using their natural resources to build a cosmopolitan culture that was as influential in the Mediterranean as it was in Southeast Asia. 
<h4>Did You Know?</h4>
Korkai is frequently mentioned in ancient Tamil literature and was known for producing some of the finest pearls.
